{{Zoroastrianism}} The '''{{lang|ae|Yasht}}s''' (''{{lang|ae|Yašt}}'') are a collection of twenty-one hymns in the [[Avesta|Younger Avestan]] language. Each of these hymns invokes a specific [[Zoroastrianism|Zoroastrian]] divinity or concept. ''Yasht'' chapter and verse pointers are traditionally abbreviated as ''Yt.''
==Overview== The word ''yasht'' derives from Middle Persian 𐭩𐭱𐭲 yašt (“prayer, worship”) probably from [[Avestan]] ''𐬫𐬀𐬱𐬙𐬀‎'' (yašta, “honored”), from ''𐬫𐬀𐬰‎'' (yaz, “to worship, honor”), from [[Proto-Indo-European language|Proto-Indo-European]] ''*yeh₂ǵ-''<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Degener|first=Almuth|date=2007-06|title=Cheung, Johnny: Etymological Dictionary of the Iranian Verb|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1007/s10783-008-9057-2|journal=Indo-Iranian Journal|volume=50|issue=2|pages=199–201|doi=10.1007/s10783-008-9057-2|issn=0019-7246}}</ref> or ''*Hyaǵ-''<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ringe|first=Don|date=2001|title=Review of “Lexikon der indogermanischen Verben” by Helmut Rix, et al.|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1075/dia.18.1.15rin|journal=Diachronica International Journal for Historical Linguistics. Founded by E.F.K. Koerner, General Editor, 1984–2001|volume=18|issue=1|pages=184–187|doi=10.1075/dia.18.1.15rin|issn=0176-4225}}</ref>, and several hymns of the ''[[Yasna]]'' liturgy that "venerate by praise" are—in tradition—also nominally called ''yasht''s. These "hidden" Yashts are: the ''[[Barsom]] Yasht'' (''Yasna'' 2), another ''[[Haoma|Hom]] Yasht'' in ''Yasna'' 9-11, the ''Bhagan Yasht'' of ''Yasna'' 19-21, a hymn to [[Ashi]] in ''Yasna'' 52, another [[Sarosh]] ''Yasht'' in ''Yasna'' 57, the praise of the (hypostasis of) "prayer" in ''Yasna'' 58, and a hymn to the [[Ahurani]] in ''Yasna'' 68. Since these are a part of the primary liturgy, they do not count among the twenty-one hymns of the ''Yasht'' collection.
All the hymns of the ''Yasht'' collection "are written in what appears to be prose, but which, for a large part, may originally have been a (basically) eight-syllable verse, oscillating between four and thirteen syllables, and most often between seven and nine."<ref name="Kellens_1989_38">{{harvnb|Kellens|1989|p=38}}.</ref>
Most of the ''[[yazata]]''s that the individual ''Yasht''s praise also have a dedication in the [[Zoroastrian calendar]]. The exceptions are [[Drvaspa]] and [[Vanant]].
